{{for|the George Seddon book|Sense of Place}}

The term '''sense of place''' has been used in many different ways. It is a characteristic that some geographic [[Location (geography)|places]] have and some do not,<ref name="Yi-Fu">{{cite book|last1=Tuan|first1=Yi-Fu|title=Space and place: The perspective of experience|date=1977|publisher=University of Minnesota press|location=Minneapolis}}</ref> while to others it is a feeling or perception held by people (not by the place itself).<ref name="Agnew">{{cite book|last1=Agnew|first1=J.A.|last2=Duncan|first2=J.S.|title=The power of place: Bringing together geographical and sociological imaginations|date=1989|publisher=Unwin Hyman Publishers|location=Boston}}</ref><ref name="Altman">{{cite book|last1=Altman, ed.|first1=I.|last2=Low, ed.|first2=S.M.|title=Place attachment. Human behavior and environment: Advances in theory and research|date=1992|publisher=Plenum Press|location=New York}}</ref>  It is often used in relation to those characteristics that make a place special or unique, as well as to those that foster a sense of authentic human attachment and belonging.<ref name="Casey 1">{{cite journal|last1=Casey|first1=E.S.|title=Between geography and philosophy: what does it mean to be in place world?|journal=Annals of the Association of American Geographers|date=2001|volume=91|pages=683–693|doi=10.1111/0004-5608.00266}}</ref>  Others, such as geographer [[Yi-Fu Tuan]], have pointed to senses of place that are not "positive," such as fear.<ref>Tuan, Yi-Fu (1980). ''Landscapes of Fear''. Oxford: Basil Blackwell.</ref>  Some students and educators engage in "[[place-based education]]" in order to improve their "sense(s) of place," as well as to use various aspects of place as educational tools in general.<ref>Simandan, D. 2013. Introduction: Learning as a geographical process. The Professional Geographer, 65(3), pp. 363-368. https://doi.org/10.1080/00330124.2012.693872</ref><ref>Simandan, D 2013. Learning wisdom through geographical dislocations. The Professional Geographer, 65(3), pp. 390-395. https://doi.org/10.1080/00330124.2012.693876</ref><ref>Sun, Y., Chan, R.C. and Chen, H., 2016. Learning with Geographical Sensitivity: Place-Based Education and Its Praxis. The Professional Geographer, 68(4), pp.574-583.</ref> The term is used in urban and rural studies in relation to place-making and place-attachment of communities to their environment or homeland.<ref name="Groat">{{cite book|last1=Groat, ed.|first1=L.|title=Giving places meaning: Readings in environmental psychology|date=1995|publisher=Academic Press|location=San Diego}}</ref>

==Geographic place==

[[Cultural geography|Cultural geographers]], [[anthropologists]], [[sociologists]] and [[urban planners]] study why certain places hold special meaning to particular people or animals.<ref name="Spretnak">{{cite book|last1=Spretnak|first1=C.|title=The resurgence of the real: Body, nature and place in a hypermodern world|date=1997|publisher=Addison-Wesley Publishers|location=New York}}</ref> Places said to have a strong "sense of place" have a strong [[identity (social science)|identity]]  that is deeply felt by inhabitants and visitors.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bloom|first1=W.|title=Personal identity, national identity and international relations|date=1990|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge}}</ref><ref name="Allen">{{cite book|last1=Allen|first1=J.|last2=Massey|first2=D.|last3=Cochrane|first3=A.|title=Rethinking the Region|date=1998|publisher=Routledge|location=London}}</ref> Sense of place is a social [[phenomenon]].<ref name="Agnew 2">{{cite book|last1=Agnew|first1=J.|title=Making political geography|date=2002|publisher=Arnold Press|location=London}}</ref> Codes aimed at protecting, preserving and enhancing places felt to be of value include "[[World Heritage Site]]" designations, the British "[[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]" controls and the American "[[National Historic Landmark]]" designation.

==Placelessness==

Places that lack a "sense of place" are sometimes referred to as "placeless" or "inauthentic”;cultural geographer, Edward Relph investigates the "placelessness" of these locations<ref>Relph, Edward, Place and Placelessness</ref> anthropologist [[Marc Augé]] calls these "non-places."<ref name="Augé">{{cite book|last1=Augé|first1=Marc|title=Non-Places: Introduction to an Anthropology of Supermodernity|date=1995|publisher=Verson Books|location=New York}}</ref>  Stepping against the kind of reductive thinking that placelessness can lead to, in his book, The Practice of Everyday Life, Jesuit philosopher [[Michel de Certeau]] argues that another way of seeing placelessness is to see it as space. For de Certeau,"space is merely composed of intersections of mobile elements" that are not in stasis (117). Place, on the other hand, is space that has been ordered in some way to serve some human need"(117). A park, for instance, is a place that has been constructed "in accord with which elements are distributed in relationships of coexistence"(117) and therefore "implies an indication of stability"(117). de Certeau's ideas became instrumental in understanding the intersections of power and social relations in the construction of place. For de Certeau, placelessness, or "space" was a site for freedom or at least it is the site for what Timotheus Vermeulen sees as "potentially anarchic movement"<ref>https://frieze.com/article/space-place</ref>    Outside of de Certeau's ideas, Placeless landscapes are seen as those that have no special relationship to the places in which they are located—they could be anywhere; roadside strip [[shopping mall]]s, [[filling stations|gas/petrol stations]] and [[convenience store]]s, [[fast food]] chains, and chain [[department store]]s have been cited as examples of placeless landscape elements.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Davis|first1=Mike|title=City of Quartz: Excavating the Future in Los Angeles|date=1990|publisher=Vintage Press, Penquin Books|location=New York|isbn=9780679738060}}</ref>  Some historic sites or districts that have been heavily commercialized for [[tourism]] and new housing estates are defined as having lost their sense of place.<ref name="Harvey 1">{{cite book|last1=Harvey|first1=D.C.|title=From space to place and back again: reflections on the condition of post modernity|date=1993|publisher=Routledge|location=London}}</ref> [[Gertrude Stein]]'s "there is no there there" has been used as a description of such places.<ref>''Anyone's Autobiography'', 1937: see [[Gertrude Stein]].</ref>

Human geographers and social psychologists have studied how a sense of place develops, including the importance of comparisons between places, learning from elders and observing natural disasters and other events.  Of particular note is the importance of childhood experiences.<ref>Measham TG (2006) Learning about environments: The significance of primal landscapes, Environmental Management 38(3), pp. 426–434</ref>  Environmental psychologists have quantified links between exposure to natural environments in childhood and environmental preferences later in life.<ref>Bixler, R. D., M. F. Floyd, and W. E. Hammitt. (2002). Environmental socialization: Quantitative tests of the childhood play hypothesis, Environment and Behavior 34(6) pp. 795–818</ref> Learning about surrounding environments during childhood is strongly influenced by the direct experience of playing, as well as through the role of family, culture, and community.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Derr | first1 = V | year = 2002 | title = Children's sense of place in northern New Mexico | url = | journal = Journal of Environmental Psychology | volume = 22 | issue = 1–2| pages = 125–137 | doi=10.1006/jevp.2002.0252}}</ref>  The special bond which develops between children and their childhood environments has been called a "primal landscape" by human geographers.<ref>Gayton (1996) Landscapes of the Interior: Re-explorations of Nature and the Human Spirit. Gabriola Island, Canada: New Society Publishers</ref> This childhood landscape forms part of an individual's identity and constitutes a key point of comparison for considering subsequent places later in life. As people move around as adults, they tend to consider new places in relation to this baseline landscape experienced during childhood.<ref>Measham, TG (2007) Primal Landscapes: insights for education from empirical research on ways of learning about environments, International Research in Geographical and Environmental Education 16 (4) pp. 339–350</ref> Sense of place is used as  a model for community-based psychosocial support programs.<ref>Prewitt Diaz, J.O. and Dayal, A. (2008). Sense of Place: A Model for Community Based psychosocial support programs. Australasian Journal of Disaster and Trauma Studies. http://www.massey.ac.nz/~trauma/issues/2008-1/prewitt_diaz.htm[[Joseph O. Prewitt Diaz]]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/09614524.2013.772120 | volume=23 | title=Fostering rural sense of place: the missing piece in Uturu, Nigeria | year=2013 | journal=Development in Practice | pages=264–277 | last1 = Chigbu | first1 = U.E.}}</ref>

